│ Understanding the Issue:\nThe transformed IR produced by loop-vectorize  │
│ with -force-vector-width=1 -force-vector-interleave=2 miscompiles a loop │
│ with an early exit condition. In the source, when the early-exit is      │
│ taken, the returned value depends on the current scalar induction        │
│ variable (iv). In the vectorized target, when the early-exit is taken,   │
│ the return PHIs incorrectly use the vector preheader's %offset.idx       │
│ directly without selecting the part/lane corresponding to the first      │
│ active exit, yielding 0 instead of the expected 2 in the attached Alive2 │
│ counterexample.\n\nThis happens particularly when VF=1 (scalar VF) but   │
│ UF>1 (interleaving), where we still have multiple parts; the code needs  │
│ to select the correct part value corresponding to the active early-exit  │
│ condition. However, the current code path skips adding the               │
│ selection/extract when VF is scalar.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\n- The   │
│ initial VPlan skeleton wires exit PHIs for the return block to incoming  │
│ values from the vector path (%offset.idx) and middle block constants.\n- │
│ Later, VPlanTransforms::handleEarlyExits introduces middle.split and     │
│ vector.early.exit blocks and is supposed to update exit PHIs. The        │
│ function contains logic to:\n  - extract the last lane of the latch exit │
│ incoming value when there are two predecessors (middle + early exit),    │
│ and\n  - add FirstActiveLane + ExtractLane to the incoming value from    │
│ the early exit to select the correct element.\n- In the target IR        │
│ provided by the pass, the incoming value from vector.early.exit remains  │
│ as %offset.idx with no extract/selection, indicating the update was      │
│ skipped.\n- The skip is controlled by this condition in                  │
│ handleEarlyExits:\n  if (!IncomingFromEarlyExit->isLiveIn() &&           │
│ LoopVectorizationPlanner::getDecisionAndClampRange(IsVector, Range)) {   │
│ ... add FirstActiveLane/ExtractLane ... }\n  where IsVector checks       │
│ VF.isVector(). With -force-vector-width=1, VF is scalar, so the          │
│ condition is false and the update is not applied.\n\n3. Root Cause       │
│ Analysis:\nThe current guard in VPlanTransforms::handleEarlyExits only   │
│ performs the lane/part selection for the early-exit incoming value when  │
│ the range contains vector VFs. For VF=1 (scalar) with UF>1, the loop     │
│ still has multiple parts due to interleaving, and early exits can happen │
│ in any part. Failing to select the corresponding part's value results in │
│ wiring the wrong value (%offset.idx from the first part) to the exit     │
│ PHIs.\n\nTherefore, the root cause is the overly restrictive condition   │
│ that ties the update solely to vector VFs, ignoring interleaving (UF>1)  │
│ scenarios with scalar VF.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\nWe should       │
│ ensure incoming values from early exit are updated to select the correct │
│ part/lane in both vector and scalar VF cases. The simplest robust change │
│ is to remove dependence on                                               │
│ LoopVectorizationPlanner::getDecisionAndClampRange(IsVector, Range) for  │
│ the early-exit incoming value update, and always add FirstActiveLane +   │
│ ExtractLane when the incoming is not a live-in value. This allows the    │
│ selection logic to apply for UF>1 even when VF=1.\n\nEdit details:\n-    │
│ File: llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VPlanTransforms.cpp\n- Location: In  │
│ handleEarlyExits, lines 3046-3056\n- Change: Remove the range clamp      │
│ predicate relying on VF.isVector(), and unconditionally apply the        │
│ FirstActiveLane + ExtractLane replacement for IncomingFromEarlyExit when │
│ it is not live-in.\n\nProposed replacement for lines 3046-3056:\n\n  //  │
│ When the incoming value is computed in the loop, update it to select\n   │
│ // the element corresponding to the first active lane/part that          │
│ triggered\n  // the early exit. This is needed for both vector and       │
│ scalar VF cases\n  // (with UF>1), as interleaving produces multiple     │
│ parts.\n  if (!IncomingFromEarlyExit->isLiveIn()) {\n    VPValue         │
│ *FirstActiveLane = EarlyExitB.createNaryOp(\n                            │
│ VPInstruction::FirstActiveLane, {CondToEarlyExit}, nullptr,\n            │
│ \"first.active.lane\");\n    IncomingFromEarlyExit =                     │
│ EarlyExitB.createNaryOp(\n        VPInstruction::ExtractLane,            │
│ {FirstActiveLane, IncomingFromEarlyExit},\n        nullptr,              │
│ \"early.exit.value\");\n    ExitIRI->setOperand(EarlyExitIdx,            │
│ IncomingFromEarlyExit);\n  }\n\nThis keeps the logic identical but       │
│ ensures it runs irrespective of VF.isVector(). The FirstActiveLane and   │
│ ExtractLane machinery is designed to select correct lane/part and should │
│ work with UF>1 and VF=1 as used elsewhere.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nBy         │
│ removing the VF.isVector()-based guard and always updating the           │
│ early-exit incoming value (when not live-in), the pass will correctly    │
│ select the part/lane corresponding to the first active exit, fixing the  │
│ miscompile observed in the Alive2 report. This change preserves          │
│ correctness for purely vector VFs (where it already applied) and extends │
│ it to scalar VF with interleaving, aligning the vector path semantics    │
│ with the scalar loop behavior on early exits."})                         │
