│                                                                          │
│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                              │
│                                                                          │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                          │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue:                                              │
│ The transformed IR produced by loop-vectorize with -force-vector-width=1 │
│ -force-vector-interleave=2 miscompiles a loop with an early exit         │
│ condition. In the source, when the early-exit is taken, the returned     │
│ value depends on the current scalar induction variable (iv). In the      │
│ vectorized target, when the early-exit is taken, the return PHIs         │
│ incorrectly use the vector preheader's %offset.idx directly without      │
│ selecting the part/lane corresponding to the first active exit, yielding │
│ 0 instead of the expected 2 in the attached Alive2 counterexample.       │
│                                                                          │
│ This happens particularly when VF=1 (scalar VF) but UF>1 (interleaving), │
│ where we still have multiple parts; the code needs to select the correct │
│ part value corresponding to the active early-exit condition. However,    │
│ the current code path skips adding the selection/extract when VF is      │
│ scalar.                                                                  │
│                                                                          │
│ 2. Analyzing opt's Log:                                                  │
│ - The initial VPlan skeleton wires exit PHIs for the return block to     │
│ incoming values from the vector path (%offset.idx) and middle block      │
│ constants.                                                               │
│ - Later, VPlanTransforms::handleEarlyExits introduces middle.split and   │
│ vector.early.exit blocks and is supposed to update exit PHIs. The        │
│ function contains logic to:                                              │
│   - extract the last lane of the latch exit incoming value when there    │
│ are two predecessors (middle + early exit), and                          │
│   - add FirstActiveLane + ExtractLane to the incoming value from the     │
│ early exit to select the correct element.                                │
│ - In the target IR provided by the pass, the incoming value from         │
│ vector.early.exit remains as %offset.idx with no extract/selection,      │
│ indicating the update was skipped.                                       │
│ - The skip is controlled by this condition in handleEarlyExits:          │
│   if (!IncomingFromEarlyExit->isLiveIn() &&                              │
│ LoopVectorizationPlanner::getDecisionAndClampRange(IsVector, Range)) {   │
│ ... add FirstActiveLane/ExtractLane ... }                                │
│   where IsVector checks VF.isVector(). With -force-vector-width=1, VF is │
│ scalar, so the condition is false and the update is not applied.         │
│                                                                          │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                  │
│ The current guard in VPlanTransforms::handleEarlyExits only performs the │
│ lane/part selection for the early-exit incoming value when the range     │
│ contains vector VFs. For VF=1 (scalar) with UF>1, the loop still has     │
│ multiple parts due to interleaving, and early exits can happen in any    │
│ part. Failing to select the corresponding part's value results in wiring │
│ the wrong value (%offset.idx from the first part) to the exit PHIs.      │
│                                                                          │
│ Therefore, the root cause is the overly restrictive condition that ties  │
│ the update solely to vector VFs, ignoring interleaving (UF>1) scenarios  │
│ with scalar VF.                                                          │
│                                                                          │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s):                                               │
│ We should ensure incoming values from early exit are updated to select   │
│ the correct part/lane in both vector and scalar VF cases. The simplest   │
│ robust change is to remove dependence on                                 │
│ LoopVectorizationPlanner::getDecisionAndClampRange(IsVector, Range) for  │
│ the early-exit incoming value update, and always add FirstActiveLane +   │
│ ExtractLane when the incoming is not a live-in value. This allows the    │
│ selection logic to apply for UF>1 even when VF=1.                        │
│                                                                          │
│ Edit details:                                                            │
│ - File: llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VPlanTransforms.cpp                │
│ - Location: In handleEarlyExits, lines 3046-3056                         │
│ - Change: Remove the range clamp predicate relying on VF.isVector(), and │
│ unconditionally apply the FirstActiveLane + ExtractLane replacement for  │
│ IncomingFromEarlyExit when it is not live-in.                            │
│                                                                          │
│ Proposed replacement for lines 3046-3056:                                │
│                                                                          │
│   // When the incoming value is computed in the loop, update it to       │
│ select                                                                   │
│   // the element corresponding to the first active lane/part that        │
│ triggered                                                                │
│   // the early exit. This is needed for both vector and scalar VF cases  │
│   // (with UF>1), as interleaving produces multiple parts.               │
│   if (!IncomingFromEarlyExit->isLiveIn()) {                              │
│     VPValue *FirstActiveLane = EarlyExitB.createNaryOp(                  │
│         VPInstruction::FirstActiveLane, {CondToEarlyExit}, nullptr,      │
│         "first.active.lane");                                            │
│     IncomingFromEarlyExit = EarlyExitB.createNaryOp(                     │
│         VPInstruction::ExtractLane, {FirstActiveLane,                    │
│ IncomingFromEarlyExit},                                                  │
│         nullptr, "early.exit.value");                                    │
│     ExitIRI->setOperand(EarlyExitIdx, IncomingFromEarlyExit);            │
│   }                                                                      │
│                                                                          │
│ This keeps the logic identical but ensures it runs irrespective of       │
│ VF.isVector(). The FirstActiveLane and ExtractLane machinery is designed │
│ to select correct lane/part and should work with UF>1 and VF=1 as used   │
│ elsewhere.                                                               │
│                                                                          │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                           │
│ By removing the VF.isVector()-based guard and always updating the        │
│ early-exit incoming value (when not live-in), the pass will correctly    │
│ select the part/lane corresponding to the first active exit, fixing the  │
│ miscompile observed in the Alive2 report. This change preserves          │
│ correctness for purely vector VFs (where it already applied) and extends │
│ it to scalar VF with interleaving, aligning the vector path semantics    │
│ with the scalar loop behavior on early exits.                            │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                          │
